metadata.initialMessage: Hey! I'm curious about your thoughts on AI in 2026. What do you think are the most exciting developments we'll see?
metadata.finalTopicGoal: Learn about their thoughts, experience, or work with agentic systems and multi-agent frameworks

conversation.speaker: Khagendra (Sender)
conversation.message: Hey! I'm curious about your thoughts on AI in 2026. What do you think are the most exciting developments we'll see?

conversation.speaker: User (Receiver)
conversation.message: Yeah, it's gonna be dope, but I'm also really curious about how all this agent stuff is gonna impact privacy in the next couple

conversation.speaker: Khagendra (Sender)
conversation.message: Yeah, I'm honestly just super stoked for agents to finally start handling complex tasks on their own without us needing to babysit them!

conversation.speaker: User (Receiver)
conversation.message: Yeah, and I'm actually gonna focus my work on building decentralized agents that keep all that personal data super safe and private.

conversation.speaker: Khagendra (Sender)
conversation.message: Yeah, it's gonna be a huge challenge to keep data local so these agents don't end up knowing way more about us than they probably should

conversation.speaker: User (Receiver)
conversation.message: Totally, but chips are getting so fast and models are shrinking so much that I think we'll be totally fine by next year.

conversation.speaker: Khagendra (Sender)
conversation.message: That's a sick project, but do you think we'll actually have enough compute power on-device to make those agents run smoothly for everyone?

conversation.speaker: User (Receiver)
conversation.message: "Honestly, just like syncing everything without it feeling super laggy has been a total headache for me lately, but what about you?

conversation.speaker: Khagendra (Sender)
conversation.message: Yeah, for sure, so what's been the trickiest part about actually building those decentralized systems for you so far?

conversation.speaker: User (Receiver)
conversation.message: Haha, I totally get it, but do you think we're finally gonna see better orchestration layers fixing that logic gap by next year?

conversation.speaker: Khagendra (Sender)
conversation.message: Oh, I've just been struggling to get agentic reasoning to stay on track without it going off on some weird tangent every few minutes.

conversation.speaker: User (Receiver)
conversation.message: Yeah, totally, and I'm honestly wondering if we'll even be doing much coding ourselves once these systems really start to click.

conversation.speaker: Khagendra (Sender)
conversation.message: Yeah, I'm hoping better planning frameworks will close that gap, but man, getting them to reason perfectly every time is still so tough.

conversation.speaker: User (Receiver)
conversation.message: That's the dream, and I'm honestly wondering if it'll make starting a company way easier or just way more competitive for all of us.

conversation.speaker: Khagendra (Sender)
conversation.message: Yeah, I think we'll mostly just be high-level architects while the agents handle all the actual syntax and boring boilerplate for us.

conversation.speaker: Khagendra (Sender)
conversation.message: Yeah, it'll probably be way easier to launch, but standing out is gonna be a total grind when everyone's using the same agents.
